<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Scottish Land and Estates</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Scottish Land &amp; Estates</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> is a membership organisation </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">which</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> represents rural landowning businesses across Scotland. Our membership of over 2,500 is heavily involved in a wide variety of land based business sectors, all of which are vitally important to rural prosperity and sustainability.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Today landowners’ business interests</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> are very diverse and for the majority of our members their landholdings are relatively modest in size: over half of our members own less than 450 hectares of land. Whilst diverse in size and makeup, our members are united in their passion for Scotland’s land. They take the responsibility of land stewardship extremely seriously and are significant contributors to the vitality of rural communities as well as helping underpin the future economic sustainability of the rural sector.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The organisation is actively involved in the Scottish Government’s Land Reform Review and our submission to the review is attached for consideration. We are also members of the stakeholder group for the Community Empowerment and Renewal Bill, which is considering ways in which to improve local democracy and decision making, and empower communities th</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">oughout Scotland. We have therefore limited our response to the Scottish Affairs Committee to general principles and specific issues reserved to Westminster.  </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In addition, we have limited our response to the questions asked by the Scottish Affairs Committee rather than countering the claims made in the discussion paper by Wightman et al. However, we believe that many of the claims made in the paper are unfounded or misleading.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Scotland’s private landowners have a clear vision for the future of rural Scotland – to help build and sustain a healthy economy where private and community enterprises can flourish in harmony. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Our 2,500 members, across Scotland, believe this is the most productive way forward and would welcome the creation of a progressive political and legislative environment where this approach is encouraged. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Landowners are part of the communities in which they live and work – to divide one sector of a community with the rest is not conducive to a successful Scotland.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Scottish Land &amp; Estates contends that a modern land reform debate should focus on the best use of land and what the desired outcomes of land management should be, and then, how best these outcomes can be delivered to produce a range of primary and secondary outcomes, rather than simply on who owns the land</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">. We subscribe to the view in Warren &amp; McKee 2011 (The Scottish Revolution? Evaluating the impacts of post devolution land reform) that ‘land reform is about finding a mix of rights and responsibilities which will facilitate the development </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">of a healthy society and a healthy environment.’  </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We refute the principle that </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">the pattern of land ownership in Scotland is in some way detrimental to economic or social development and do not believe that </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">there is any need for further </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">artificial measures to </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">create a more diverse pattern of land ownership. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Scottish Land &amp; Estates</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> do</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">es</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> not oppose community right to buy. Many of our members were disappointed the Land Reform Review Group </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">(LRRG) </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">appeared to focus almost exclusively on this issue rather than explore other areas of policy improvement available such as effective community planning, increased affordable housing and better local decision-making processes. We support a wide variety of community involvement and ownership models and also the principle of extending the existing community right-to-buy provisions to urban areas. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Our position remains the sale of an asset should be on the basis of willing seller, willing buyer</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:3pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We believe responsible use of land – whether in public, private or community ownership – should be the determining factor in the policy landscape</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We believe that there is definite room for improvement in the operation of current Community Right to Buy legislation and are involved in detailed discussions regarding this with the Scottish Government and other stakeholders.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We do not agree</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> that private landowners routinely engage in tax avoidance practices, nor do they in the main look to benefit from speculation in the land market – indeed many land reform activists complain that private landowners do not sell their land.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> If there are issues with the taxation framework, then criticisms should be levied at those who develop and operate it rather than those who operate lawfully within it. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Our response to the Scottish Government’s Land Reform Review contained 60 recommendations covering land reform related issues </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">– albeit land reform in the widest sense, not restricted to the transfer of assets from one group to another. We have referred to </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">some of these</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> recommendations below but ask that our submission in full is considered by the Committee as supplementary information.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Responses to the questions posed by the Scottish Affairs Committee</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How does Scotland compare to other countries in terms of the pattern of land ownership? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Much is made of the fact that some individuals in Scotland own large landholdings, </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">but </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">l</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">rge landholdings are equally as common in other countries, especially in countries where the productive value of the land is low. The figure of 432:50 is used as a conveni</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">nt headline figure but does not give</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> a true reflection of Scottish land ownership – the 432 owners are not individuals, but are legal entities which may include a large number of joint owners, trustees (including professional advisers and community representatives) or in the case of companies, shareholders. The other 50% </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">of the privately owned land in Scotland is owned by many tens of thousands – and it is worth pointing out that private land only accounts for 83% of total acreage</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> in rural Scotland</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> There has been a significant change in land ownership in Scotland in the last 20 years, with a marked increase in the extent of land owned by community </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> and, to a lesser extent</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">, conservation </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">. These increases have occurred largely due to the transfer of land from the private sector – much of it on a voluntary basis without recourse to the land reform legislation.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">As referenced above, large scale landholdings exist in other countries, including Norway and Sweden. We would suggest that comparables are best made on the outputs of our land and how it is used than the pattern of ownership.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Warren &amp; McKee make reference to the changing pattern of land ownership, stating that </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">‘the</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> formerly dualistic pattern of land ownership in Scotland, divided between private and state, has begun to fracture</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> into a myriad of pluralistic models’ and then stated that </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">‘the</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> timescale over which the success of this [change in ownership] new trend should be judged is decades or even centuries.’</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Thus the 2003 Act and other changes in land use approaches has resulted in change, further changes will undoubtedly occur, particularly if the land reform review results in improvements to the operation of legislation and wholesale review of community planning.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the benefits and disadvantages of the current pattern of land ownership, and to what extent is this pattern sustained and reinforced by subsidy and taxation arrangements? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We do not believe that the taxation framework within which landowners and rural businesses operate </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> sustaining or reinforcing a particular pattern of land ownership. With regard to subsidy – most is focused on use rather than</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> ownership. Further </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">comment</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> on this is provided below. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We would </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">stress</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> that m</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ost</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> of the tax arrangements and subsidies for </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">carrying out specific</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> activities are available to all sizes and types of owners, including community owners, many of whom are reliant on income from </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">windfarm</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> developments.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">In particular, is the current land ownership pattern contributing to, or inhibiting, economic and community development? Is it socially just? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We believe that the </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">contribution of privately owned estates is clearly evidenced – as is the benefits which can be, and are, delivered by other ownership types. The contribution to or inhibition of economic and community development depend largely on how the land is managed and not the ownership type. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> The recent research from Scottish Rural University College (attached as Appendix) found that a vibrant and strong family estate can contribute to the on-going vibrancy of rural communities. This is also </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">covered </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">in the ‘Sustainable Estates’ research from Perth College</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> which evidences the benefits of partnerships between private estates and local communities, and the widespread desire for them</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Land in the ownership of private </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> is overwhelmingly employed productively. It benefits local communities through tourism, job creation, agriculture, housing and more. Private and community ownership should not be viewed as opposite ends of a spectrum – both ensure the viability of our rural areas. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We would also like to make reference to the ability of large scale integrated landowner (regardless of whether private, public or community) to deliver multiple public benefits. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">This was exemplified at the recent SNH </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Specis</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Action Framework conference in 2012, where case study after case study highlighted that one of the b</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">iggest threats to species conservation was the fragmentation of landholdings and the consequential break-up of coherent and unified management.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">It was </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">recognised</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> within our submission to the Land Reform Review group that there was a need to improve community engagement and community involvement in land use decision making.  We have subsequently launched a Community Engagement </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Programme</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">, more information on which is provided as an Appendix.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> The Programme will support the continued development of collaborations and partnerships between estates and communities. It will also raise awareness of the current forms of community interaction already taking place on estates, and will aid in the formalization of these into best practice </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">intiatives</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Given mounting political interest in, or commitment to, a programme of land reform in Scotland, what form should this programme take? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Scottish Land &amp; Estates</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> supports a diverse pattern of ownership of land and built property, but </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">believes that </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">such diversity should not become an </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">objective</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> in itself</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">. The focus </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">of any</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> programme should be on improving the operation of current community right to buy legislation to simplify the process for those willing to sell and buy land and assets. In addition, the community planning framework must be fully revised </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">as it is not currently fit for purpose.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What sort of subsidies and grants are available to landed estate owners in Scotland? What are the advantages and disadvantages of the subsidy regime? In particular, are support payments being capitalized into land values and making these higher than they otherwise would be?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">As referred to above, subsidies and grants are available to a wide range of people who own, manage or have access to land. It is misleading to suggest that a specific grant and subsidy system for landed estate owners exist</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The system of financial payments to land managers is operated under the rules of the </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">CAP</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">, applicable throughout the EU, with a degree of flexibility for member states and within that, for parts of member states.  However, it is a principle across the EU that CAP payments </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">are made </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">to the occupiers of agricultural land, rather than to the owners as such. Where land is tenanted or otherwise managed by someone other than the owner, it will be that person, not the owner, who receives the payment.  </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Scottish Government is taking steps to ensure that payments only go to active farmers and not so called slipper farmers (which includes owners and tenants no longer actively farming).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, payments are conditional upon certain activities being carried out and upon the compliance by the occupier with the rules and regulations of the EU and member state, for example in relation to pollution control.  Payments may be made in respect of the carrying on of a farming business, or payments may be made under the </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">agri</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">-environment schemes for specific and positive land management actions, to enhance the landscape and or wildlife habitats, or to retain historic features.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">he capital value of agricultural land is </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">not dependent upon the subsidy level</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.  It will depend on expectations for the duration of such payments in future and the prospect of changes to the terms and conditions applying to their provision.  The effect will be different for tenanted land with vacant possession, the nature of the land and the profitability of farming, even with the provision of CAP payments.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">With specific regard to subsidy for the delivery of renewable energy (which is of course in line with Scottish Government climate change), we </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">provided a</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> case study </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">as an appendix </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">to illustrate the reality of how private landowners are seeking to ensure that communities share in the benefits of renewable energy developments.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How does the tax regime affect the way in which land is owned in Scotland? For instance, does it offer landed estate owners the opportunity to minimize the tax they pay, thereby increasing the value of land, adding to speculative interest (on the part of those looking for ways to minimize or avoid tax) and making it less likely that it will be made available to others? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">It is essential to underline that t</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">he entities referred to by the Committee as ‘landed estates’ are in actual fact land based businesses. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Undoubtedly, t</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ax reliefs have in the past encouraged people to invest in land or to carry out specific activities on an area of land – these tax reliefs are not restricted to private landowners and indeed many may be available to tenants as well.  </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Land based businesses, like all businesses and indeed individuals, will strive to operate in a tax efficient manner to improve the sustainability of their business or for example, to increase the resources available to reinvest in our historic built </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">environment</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We strongly refute the claims made in the 432:50 paper that private landowners routinely engage in tax avoidance measures,</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">nor do they in the main look to benefit from speculation in the land market</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Scottish Land &amp; Estates is aware of the clear legal distinction between tax evasion on the one hand and legitimate tax </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">minimisation</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> or tax planning on the other.  We </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">recognise</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> that tax evasion by not paying or under-paying taxes, normally by false or no declaration is illegal and can carry with it civil and criminal penalties.  This is primarily where loopholes in legislation which Parliament did not intend are being exploited through artificial or contrived arrangements.  Not only do we not condone such practice, but we positively welcome prosecution where it is found that someone or some entity has evaded their legal duty to pay tax.  We also </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">recognise</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> the ethical considerations in relation to some of the more aggressive forms of tax planning and tax </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">minimisation</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">, but at the same time are aware that these are legal as the law currently stands and widely used.  In addition to legality, reputational risk is an aspect most businesses and people across industries would consider on tax planning.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Tax planning is part of tax compliant </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">behaviour</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> and can take many forms and most individuals and businesses across sectors will consider ways in which they can </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">minimise</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> their tax payments.  This is not something peculiar to private landowners.  Examples of commonly used tax planning schemes may include Individual Savings Accounts (ISAs) or pensions contributions or charitable donations.  A taxpayer choosing to utilize a means of reducing tax in such ways is exercising an option made available to them in law that is entirely tax compliant provided the published conditions for saving in that way are met.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">HMRC issued General Anti-Abuse Rule Guidance (GAAR) with effect from 15 April 2013 which can strike down abusive arrangements.   We </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">strongly refute</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> any insinuation of underhand </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">behaviour</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> or malpractice on the part of any of our members who legitimately engage in lawful tax planning exercises which are not contrary to GAAR.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The G8 Lough Erne Declaration in June 2013, with its emphasis on “tax, trade and transparency” is welcomed by Scottish Land &amp; Estates to clamp down on money launderers, illegal tax evaders and corporate tax avoiders.  Progress already being made in this field by the UK and other world governments should be encouraged and this will not be helped, indeed it will be complicated, by singling out a particular aspect of a specific sector, where no particular problems exist.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Also in June, just prior to Lough Erne there was agreement reached by the UK's Overseas Territories and Crown dependencies to sign up to a tax evasion clampdown.  This agreement is welcomed by us. The Multilateral Convention on Mutual Assistance in Tax Matters - an initiative led by the </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Organisation</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) is in our view the correct approach to take.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">It should be recognized that p</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">rivate landowners make a substantial contribution to HMRC.  Typically an estate will pay </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">numerous</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> taxes</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> in many forms and across a wide range of activities.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> In</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">an increasingly global society we require a taxation environment which encourages rather than discourages inward investment.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Tax reliefs and allowances are universally available and not simply the preserve of private landowners.  There is generally a level playing field in relation to reliefs and this is regardless of size of landholding.  No reliefs are simply based on acreage, though some will rely on there being sufficient business activity on the land in question to qualify.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Agricultural Property Relief only applies to the agricultural value of farmland and includes cottages, farm buildings and farmhouses, together with the land occupied by them, as are a character appropriate to the property.  Relief is already therefore denied where the farmhouse is excessively large in relation to the farm.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Removal of reliefs and allowances may have the converse effect of making land ownership less available or accessible to both private individuals and community groups.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Many Estates are in multiple and complex ownerships rather than a single-ownership model, but this is for a variety of reasons.  Trusts may be set up to ensure stewardship of family assets; when someone is too young to handle their affairs; when someone can't handle their affairs because they are incapacitated; to pass on money or property while they are still alive or to pass on money or assets when on death under the terms of a will.  There are several types of “family” trust and each is taxed separately.  “Non-family” trusts can also be set up for different reasons for instance to operate a charity or set up a pension scheme for employees.  Trusts can therefore be set up for a particular reason at the time, but subsequently the reason can become obsolete and there may in fact not be any tax advantage at times in holding assets in a trust.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Trusts are a complex issue and Scottish Land &amp; Estates suggests that professional in</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ut is received from the Law Society of Scotland and ICAS. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How easy is it for communities in Scotland to take ownership of land and other assets? Should it be made easier in the light of the substantial achievements of existing community ownership groups?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">There is undoubtedly room for improvement in the operation of the Community Right to Buy provisions of the 2003 Land Reform Act. We are involved in detailed discussions with the Scottish Government and other stakeholders regarding these improvements.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">It is critical that community ownership is not viewed as an end in itself</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> – it is a vehicle for delivering economic, social and environmental benefits. There have indeed been some substantial achievements by existing community ownership groups but community ownership is not universally successful.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:3pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We believe that there should not be a sole focus on ownership by communities – there are many ways in which communities can become empowered and play a more active part in </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">shaping </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">land use. There are many instances of good collaborative arrangements between communities and those who own, manage or control land so there are significant opportunities for improving these relationships. Scottish Land &amp; Estates believes that much broader collaborative arrangements are required to support communities involving not just the public sector agencies and usual players but third sector, private sector and other organisations. There needs to be much greater focus on, and enhancement of, current structures is required, before embarking on ‘radical’ change. We believe that this approach would deliver the ‘mix of rights and responsibilities which will facilitate the development of a healthy society and a healthy environment.’</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How easy is it for tenant farmers in Scotland to buy their farms? Should they be granted an absolute right to buy? Would such a right be compatible with human rights conventions and declarations?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We have provided our views on this devolved issue to the Scottish Government, and will engage in discussions relating to this matter as part of the forthcoming Scottish Government Agricultural Holdings Review. In summary, tenant farmers are currently able to purchase their farms and many do. This is of course only where there is a willing seller. We do not believe that an Absolute Right to Buy for tenant farmers can be deemed to be compatible with human rights conventions, nor is it conducive to a </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">vibrant tenanted sector.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How easy is it for land in public ownership to be transferred to communities and other private individuals, where that would be in the public interest? Should steps be taken to make it easier? For instance, should the UK and Scottish Governments compile a register showing land and assets for disposal? Should there be changes in the way in which such land and assets are valued? What UK Treasury rules are relevant to this area? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Scottish Land &amp; Estates is aware of many instances where the delivery of benefits which could be achieved through the transfer of land in public ownership to communities and private individuals. This issue is being considered as part of the deliberations on the Community Empowerment and Renewal Bill. We have not considered in detail the valuation methodology or UK Treasury rules for such transfers but would welcome their inclusion in any discussions on the matter.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Should a Land Value Tax of some sort be introduced in Scotland, as a replacement or addition to council tax and business rates?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="49" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Scottish Land &amp; Estates</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> does not support Land Value Tax</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ation</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">, either as a replacement for or as an addition to Council Tax or Business Rates</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Many land based business are already experiencing difficulties in this challenging economic climate, and any tax imposed on the value of the land could have negative implications for a number of industry sectors, including farming.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p></div></body></html>